[2] USA (Michigan)
Date: Fri 8 Jul 2011
Source: FreshPlaza [edited]
http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=83160


Fungus wreaks havoc on Michigan crops
-------------------------------------
A devastating fungus that can affect anything that grows on a vine is
wreaking havoc on some Michigan farms. The Downy Mildew fungus spreads
by air, usually originating in the southern US. It can also spread by
transplants brought to local greenhouses. "You never know when it'll
show up, and it's very difficult to control," said Jason Ruhlig,
Ruhlig's Farms and Greenhouses. He says if the fungus strikes early
enough, it can cut cucumber yield by as much as 60 percent. "You see
yellowing in the cucumbers," he said. "Nobody wants a yellow
cucumber."

No plants are completely resistant to the fungus, but farmers can try
to prevent it by raising tolerant varieties of crops and using
fungicides.

Ruined Michigan cucumbers:
http://www.freshplaza.com/2011/0807/ruined_cucumber.jpg

